'''Nitta-no-shō Iseki''' (新田荘遺跡) refers to the archaeological sites related to {{ill|Nitta Manor|ja|新田荘|12=draft|12=draft}}, a shōen (estate) in {{ill|Kōzuke Province|ja|上野国|12=draft|12=draft}}'s {{ill|Nitta District|ja|新田郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, corresponding to modern {{ill|Ōta|ja|太田市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Gunma Prefecture|ja|群馬県|12=draft|12=draft}}. The estate encompassed the entire Nitta District, parts of {{ill|Seta District|ja|勢多郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Sai District|ja|佐位郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, and portions of {{ill|Musashi Province|ja|武蔵国|12=draft|12=draft}}'s {{ill|Hanzawa District|ja|榛沢郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, mainly comprising the {{ill|Ōmama alluvial fan|ja|大間々扇状地|12=draft|12=draft}} and the floodplain of the {{ill|Tonegawa River|ja|利根川|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>Tanaka Daiki, ed., *Series: Research on Medieval Samurai of Kantō, Vol. 3: The Nitta Clan of Kōzuke*, Yoshikōshō Publishing, June 2011, ISBN 978-4864030342.</ref> The {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|12=draft|12=draft}} mentions "Nitta Station" in Kōzuke Province, and the {{ill|Wamyō Ruijushō|ja|和名類聚抄|12=draft|12=draft}} lists "Nitta District's Ekiya-gō." Established as the ancestral land of the {{ill|Nitta clan|ja|新田氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, a samurai family of medieval Japan, Nitta Manor is unique among eastern shōen for its detailed documentation in historical records such as the {{ill|Chōrakuji Documents|ja|長楽寺文書|12=draft|12=draft}} and the Masaki Documents. In 2000 (Heisei 12), eleven locations associated with the Nitta clan's heritage were designated as National Historic Sites under the title "Nitta-no-shō Iseki."
== History of Nitta Manor == * In the mid-Heian period, the district is mentioned in the {{ill|Wamyō Ruijushō|ja|和名類聚抄|12=draft|12=draft}}, compiled during the Shōhei era (931–938), noting "Nitta District" and "Nitta Station" along the {{ill|Tōsandō|ja|東山道|12=draft|12=draft}} route, including the Musashi Road. * 1108 (Ten'nin 1): The major eruption of Mount Asama deposited ash (Asama B Tephra) across northern Kantō, devastating the region. * 1142 (Kōji 1): Minamoto no Yoshikuni establishes the Ashikaga Manor. * 1143 (Kōji 2): Minamoto no Yoshikuni establishes the Yanada Mikuriya. * 1150 (Kyūan 6): Minamoto no Yoshikuni burns down the residence of Fujiwara no Saneyoshi, the Grand Minister of the Right, and retreats to the Ashikaga estate in Shimotsuke Province after being exiled by imperial decree. Subsequently, Yoshikuni begins developing the Nitta District with his eldest son, {{ill|Nitta Yoshishige|ja|新田義重|12=draft|12=draft}}. * 1155 (Kyūju 2): Minamoto no Yoshikuni dies at the Yoshishige residence in Nitta District. * 1157 (Hōgen 2): Nineteen settlements in the "unclaimed villages" developed by Yoshikuni and Yoshishige are donated to {{ill|Kongōshin-in|ja|金剛心院|12=draft|12=draft}}, the imperial wish temple of {{ill|Emperor Toba|ja|鳥羽天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, with {{ill|Fujiwara no Tadazane|ja|藤原忠雅|12=draft|12=draft}} acting as estate proprietor. Yoshishige is appointed administrator of Nitta Manor. * 1170 (Kaō 2): Nitta Manor expands to encompass all 56 settlements of Nitta District. * For a detailed timeline, see full article text above.
== Area of Nitta Manor == ; Nineteen "unclaimed villages" in 1157<ref>"Nitta Yoshishige's Testament," Masaki Documents 3.</ref>
{{columns-list|colwidth=15em| * Onnazuka<ref name=raiouhaha/> * Kamigoeda * Shimogoeda<ref>Inherited by the Iwamatsu clan via daughters of Tokugawa Yoriyasu.</ref> * Tanaka<ref name=raiouhaha/> * Ōdate * Kasukawa * Kosumi * Oshikiri<ref name=yuzurizyou/> * Deizuka * Serada<ref name=yuzurizyou/> * Mikki<ref name=yuzurizyou/> * Kamimai<ref name=nitaama/> * Shimomai<ref name=raiouhaha/> * Kamihiratsuka<ref name=yuzurizyou/> * Shimohiratsuka<ref name=yuzurizyou/> * Kizaki * Chōfukuji * Takō * Yaginuma }}
== Preservation as a National Historic Site == The following 11 locations were designated as part of the "Nitta-no-shō Iseki" National Historic Site: * Enpuku-ji Precinct (Ōta City, Bessho Town) * Jūnisho Shrine Precinct (Ōta City, Bessho Town) * Sōjiji Precinct (Ōta City, Serada Town) * Chōraku-ji Precinct (Ōta City, Serada Town) * Tōshō-gū Precinct (Ōta City, Serada Town) * Myōō-in Precinct (Ōta City, An'yōji Town) * Ikushina Shrine Precinct (Ōta City, Shinden Ichi no I Town) * Sorimachi Yakushi Ruins (Ōta City, Nitta Sorimachi) * Edano Residence Ruins (Ōta City, Nitta Kamigoda Town) * Shigaden Water Source (Ōta City, Shinden Ichi no I Town) * Yatajin Water Source (Ōta City, Nitta Daikon Town) <ref name=yuzurizyou>「『新田義重譲状』正木文書2」新田義重は子・世良田義季とその母に譲る。大部分は世良田氏に伝領</ref> <ref name=nitaama>新田義兼後家「新田尼」より岩松氏へ伝領</ref> <ref name=raiouhaha>世良田義季母より本宗家へ伝領</ref>
