[[sn:Nitta Manor Ruins]] [[ja:新田荘遺跡]] [[en:Nitta Manor Ruins]]

'''Nitta-no-shō Iseki''' (新田荘遺跡) refers to the archaeological sites related to {{ill|Nitta Manor|ja|新田荘|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nitta Manor|qq=}}, a shōen (estate) in {{ill|Kōzuke Province|ja|上野国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōzuke Province|qq=}}'s {{ill|Nitta District|ja|新田郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nitta District|qq=}}, corresponding to modern {{ill|Ōta|ja|太田市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōta|qq=}}, {{ill|Gunma Prefecture|ja|群馬県|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gunma Prefecture|qq=}}. The estate encompassed the entire Nitta District, parts of {{ill|Seta District|ja|勢多郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Seta District|qq=}}, {{ill|Sai District|ja|佐位郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sai District|qq=}}, and portions of {{ill|Musashi Province|ja|武蔵国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Musashi Province|qq=}}'s {{ill|Hanzawa District|ja|榛沢郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hanzawa District|qq=}}, mainly comprising the {{ill|Ōmama alluvial fan|ja|大間々扇状地|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmama alluvial fan|qq=}} and the floodplain of the {{ill|Tonegawa River|ja|利根川|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tonegawa River|qq=}}.<ref>Tanaka Daiki, ed., *Series: Research on Medieval Samurai of Kantō, Vol. 3: The Nitta Clan of Kōzuke*, Yoshikōshō Publishing, June 2011, ISBN 978-4864030342.</ref> The {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Engishiki|qq=}} mentions "Nitta Station" in Kōzuke Province, and the {{ill|Wamyō Ruijushō|ja|和名類聚抄|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wamyō Ruijushō|qq=}} lists "Nitta District's Ekiya-gō." Established as the ancestral land of the {{ill|Nitta clan|ja|新田氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nitta clan|qq=}}, a samurai family of medieval Japan, Nitta Manor is unique among eastern shōen for its detailed documentation in historical records such as the {{ill|Chōrakuji Documents|ja|長楽寺文書|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōrakuji Documents|qq=}} and the Masaki Documents. In 2000 (Heisei 12), eleven locations associated with the Nitta clan's heritage were designated as National Historic Sites under the title "Nitta-no-shō Iseki."
== History of Nitta Manor == * In the mid-Heian period, the district is mentioned in the {{ill|Wamyō Ruijushō|ja|和名類聚抄|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wamyō Ruijushō|qq=}}, compiled during the Shōhei era (931–938), noting "Nitta District" and "Nitta Station" along the {{ill|Tōsandō|ja|東山道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōsandō|qq=}} route, including the Musashi Road. * 1108 (Ten'nin 1): The major eruption of Mount Asama deposited ash (Asama B Tephra) across northern Kantō, devastating the region. * 1142 (Kōji 1): Minamoto no Yoshikuni establishes the Ashikaga Manor. * 1143 (Kōji 2): Minamoto no Yoshikuni establishes the Yanada Mikuriya. * 1150 (Kyūan 6): Minamoto no Yoshikuni burns down the residence of Fujiwara no Saneyoshi, the Grand Minister of the Right, and retreats to the Ashikaga estate in Shimotsuke Province after being exiled by imperial decree. Subsequently, Yoshikuni begins developing the Nitta District with his eldest son, {{ill|Nitta Yoshishige|ja|新田義重|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nitta Yoshishige|qq=}}. * 1155 (Kyūju 2): Minamoto no Yoshikuni dies at the Yoshishige residence in Nitta District. * 1157 (Hōgen 2): Nineteen settlements in the "unclaimed villages" developed by Yoshikuni and Yoshishige are donated to {{ill|Kongōshin-in|ja|金剛心院|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kongōshin-in|qq=}}, the imperial wish temple of {{ill|Emperor Toba|ja|鳥羽天皇|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Toba|qq=}}, with {{ill|Fujiwara no Tadazane|ja|藤原忠雅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujiwara no Tadazane|qq=}} acting as estate proprietor. Yoshishige is appointed administrator of Nitta Manor. * 1170 (Kaō 2): Nitta Manor expands to encompass all 56 settlements of Nitta District. * For a detailed timeline, see full article text above.
